The '''geology of Bolivia''' comprises a variety of different [[lithology|lithologies]] as well as [[plate tectonics|tectonic]] and [[depositional environment|sedimentary environments]]. On a synoptic scale, geological units coincide with topographical units. The country is divided into a mountainous western area affected by the [[subduction]] processes in the Pacific and an eastern lowlands of stable [[platform (geology)|platforms]] and [[shield (geology)|shields]]. The Bolivian [[Andes]] is divided into three main ranges; these are from west to east: the [[Cordillera Occidental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Occidental]] that makes up the border to [[Chile]] and host several active [[volcano]]es and [[geothermal]] areas, [[Cordillera Central (Bolivia)|Cordillera Central]] (in some contexts also called Cordillera Oriental) once extensively mined for [[silver]] and [[tin]] and the relatively low [[Cordillera Oriental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Oriental]] that rather than being a range by its own is the eastern continuation of the Central Cordillera as a [[fold and thrust belt]]. Between the Occidental and Central Cordillera the approximately 3,750-meter-high [[Altiplano]] high plateau extends.<ref>[http://www.hc-solar.de/Bericht_AR_2004_en_cm.pdf The Use of Solar Energy for Improving the Living Conditions in Altiplano/Argentina]</ref> This basin hosts several freshwater lakes, including [[Lake Titicaca]] as well as salt-covered [[dry lake]]s that bring testimony of past climate changes and lake cycles. The eastern lowlands and sub-Andean zone in [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]], [[Chuquisaca Department|Chuquisaca]], and [[Tarija Department]]s was once an old [[Paleozoic]] [[sedimentary basin]] that hosts valuable [[petroleum reserve|hydrocarbon reserves]]. Further east close to the border with Brazil lies the Guaporé Shield, made up of stable [[Precambrian]] crystalline rock.

==Andes==
{{see also|Andean orogeny}}
[[File:Nevado Sajama.jpg|thumb|6,542 meter high [[Nevado Sajama]] is one of several volcanoes along Cordillera Occidental]]
The Andes of Bolivia began to rise about 200 million years ago (mya) during the [[Jurassic]]. The western margin of what is now South America had been the place of several other [[orogeny|orogenies]] before the Andes rose. It has been hypothesized that the central Andes gained its great height 26 to 14 mya as result of a compressive [[fault (geology)|failure]] of the [[lithosphere]] beneath Bolivia and neighboring areas.<ref>[http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/geology Geology of the Altiplano], [[Oregon State University]]</ref> The great heights of the Altiplano, Codillera Occidental and Cordillera Oriental are [[isostacy|isostatically]] compensated  by an up to 70&nbsp;km deep [[crust (geology)|crust]]. Climate has responded to the formation of this important topographic barrier. It is not clear, however, if the rise of the Andes simply caused the extreme aridity of [[Atacama Desert]] and adjacent parts of Bolivia or if a preexisting [[desert climate]] and associated low erosion rates allowed the mountains to build up to their current heights.<ref>[http://www.efn.uncor.edu/departamentos/GeoBas/materias/estratigrafiaygeologia/Home_archivos/tp/mod3/ClimateChange.pdf Neogene climate change and uplift in the Atacama Desert, Chile]</ref><ref name="docs.google.com">Garcia-Castellanos, D., 2007. [https://docs.google.com/uc?id=0B_xuyENh5ksFMzdiZjg0NGUtNWQ5Zi00YTU0LThkODctODA3ZWMxYjAzNTI2&export=download&hl=en The role of climate in high plateau formation. Insights from numerical experiments]. Earth Planet. Sci. Lett. 257, 372–390, doi:10.1016/j.epsl.2007.02.039</ref><ref>[http://arjournals.annualreviews.org/doi/pdf/10.1146/annurev.earth.35.031306.140158?cookieSet=1 Tectonics and Climate of the Southern Central Andes], ''Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences'', 2007. <br/>Cite: ''"precipitation and erosion may influence the kinematics and locus of tectonic activity in orogens."''</ref><ref>David R. Montgomery, Greg Balco and Sean D. Willett. 2001 [http://geology.gsapubs.org/content/29/7/579.full Climate, tectonics, and the morphology of the Andes]<br/>Cite: ''"...like tectonics, nonuniform erosion due to large-scale climate patterns is a first-order control on the topographic evolution of the Andes."''</ref> A hypothesis holds that scarce sediment supply to the [[Atacama Trench]] caused by arid climate induced high [[shear stress]]es in the [[subduction]] process that enhanced the Andean mountain building.<ref>Lamb and Davis. 2003. [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v425/n6960/abs/nature02049.html Cenozoic climate change as a possible cause for the rise of the Andes], ''Nature''</ref>

===Western Cordillera===
The Western Cordillera is made up by a series of active and extinct volcanoes rising from the western edge of the Altiplano plateau. This range divides the Chilean watersheds of [[Salar de Atacama]] and the Pacific from the [[endorheic basin|endorheic]] Altiplano basin. The western volcanoes of Bolivia are part of the Central Volcanic Zone of the Andes, a major upper [[Cenozoic]] volcanic province.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0012821X78900080|title=Upper Cenozoic Volcanism in the Central Andes – Ages and Volumes|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=41|issue=2|pages=175|doi=10.1016/0012-821X(78)90008-0|year=1978|last1=Baker|first1=M.C.W|last2=Francis|first2=P.W}}</ref> Volcanic eruptions in Bolivia are scarce, the latest one occurred in [[Irruputuncu]] in 1995. Volcanic hazards do not represent any threat to the major populated centres which are all in the eastern Altiplano or further east, far away from the volcanic centers. Although the Western Cordillera concentrates most active volcanoes (volcanoes active in the last 10000 years) many old large [[stratovolcano]]es rises up to 100&nbsp;km away from the main line of the Western Cordillera.

===Altiplano plateau===
{{further|Altiplano Basin}}
[[File:Laguna Colorada 1.jpg|thumb|[[Laguna Colorada]] in the southern Altiplano lies just east of [[Cordillera Occidental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Occidental]]'s volcanoes (background mountain).]]
The Altiplano plateau or Meseta del Collasuyu to differentiate it from other Andean [[high plateau]]x is a wide and long-lived intermontane sedimentary basin with no outlet; it is [[endorheic]]. The Altiplano is an infill of [[sediment|sedimentary material]] from both [[Cordillera Occidental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Occidental]] and [[Cordillera Oriental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Oriental]]. The origin of the Altiplano and its great height has long been major question among geologists. Today the Altiplano is believed to have been an early [[foreland basin]] of the "proto-Andes" that got uplifted by [[orogeny|crustal shortening]] in the [[Miocene|Late Miocene]].<ref name="docs.google.com"/><ref>Lamb, Hoke, Kennan, Dewey. 1996. [http://www.tectonicanalysis.net/site/download/Lamb97_Central_Andes_Evolution.pdf Cenozoic evolution of the Central Andes in Bolivia and northern Chile].</ref>

The Bolivian Altiplano hosts the world's largest reserves of [[lithium]]. These reserves are in the salt-saturated waters of [[Salar de Uyuni]] and [[Coipasa Lake|Salar de Coipasa]], neither of which are currently being commercially exploited for lithium. Salt is extracted from the saltars in minor amounts to be sold as [[table salt]] after being added [[iodine]] from [[Chile]].

===Eastern Cordillera===
{{see also|Bolivian tin belt}}
[[File:Valle de la Luna - La Paz - Bolivia.jpg|thumb|[[Erosion]] landscapes like [[Valle de la Luna (Bolivia)|Valle de la Luna]] near [[La Paz]] are common in the Central Cordillera and the Sub-Andean Zone]]
Cordillera Oriental is made up of a bended arc of plutons. The bend occurs at the latitude of [[Cochabamba]] and corresponds to eastward projection of the [[Orocline|Arica elbow]], the bend of south Amicas coastline at the Peru-Chile border. North of the bend Cordillera Centrals [[batholith]]s are northwest-southeast oriented while south of it they are north-south oriented.<ref>Hydrothermal Processes and Mineral Systems. Pages 376–381.</ref> These bodies of [[granite|granitic]] to [[granodiorite|granodioritic]] composition were formed in two episodes: the Early [[Mesozoic]] (199–180 [[million years ago|Ma]]) and the [[Neogene]] (19–8 Ma). The emplacement of these [[pluton (geology)|igneous bodies]] have been interpreted as an effect of two temporary decreases in [[subduction|subduction angle]]s  of the ancient [[Farallon Plate]].<ref>Sandra L. McBride, Ronald C. R. Robertson, Alan H. Clark and Edward Farrar. 1983.[http://www.springerlink.com/content/g3384623363606qj/fulltext.pdf Magmatie and Metallogenetie Episodes in the Northern Tin Belt, Cordillera Real, Bolivia]. Geologische Rundschau. Vol. 72. 
</ref> This arc of magmatic material hosts Bolivia's widely known [[tin]] belt as well as the famous [[silver]] mine of [[Potosí]]. These mineralizations are of the [[Porphyritic|porphyry]] [[mineralization (geology)|mineralization]] type that are typical for [[Convergent boundary|convergent plate margins]]. The [[Cordillera Real (Bolivia)|Cordillera Real]] form the northern, highly uplifted and eroded, part of the Central Cordillera.

==Lowlands and Sub-Andean zone==
{{see also|Andean Foreland Basin}}
[[File:Coroico.jpg|thumb|To reach the lowlands north of [[La Paz]] the [[Yungas]]-vegetated [[Cordillera Oriental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Oriental]] has to be passed.]]
The Sub-Andean Zone and the Northern and Eastern Lowlands share a common ancient history but has since the Andean orogeny developed to two distinct zones. While both zones share essentially the same old [[sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] [[platform (geology)|platform]] [[strata]] the strata at the Sub-Andean Zone have been folded and thrusted into a [[fold and thrust belt]] with [[structural trap]]s where [[hydrocarbon]] fluids have accumulated. The limit between the fold and thrust belt and the Eastern Lowlands is drawn by the [[Serranía del Aguaragüe]] a north-south range representing the Andean [[fold and thrust belt|thrust front]].

===Fold and thrust belt===
The relatively low [[Cordillera Oriental (Bolivia)|Cordillera Oriental]], located east of [[Cordillera Central (Bolivia)|Cordillera Central]], are part of a [[fold and thrust belt]] and exposes [[Silurian]] and [[Ordovician]] age [[strata (geology)|strata]] some of which are [[fossil]]-bearing. The fold and thrust makes up the framework of the [[catchment basin|hydrographic network]] of [[Pilcomayo River|Pilcomayo]] and other rivers. Currently one of Bolivia's most [[seismicity|seismic]] zones is the [[Cochabamba Fault Zone]] located just below the city of [[Cochabamba]] and its fertile valley. This fault zone is related to the [[Arica]] elbow and the bend in the Andes at this latitude.

===Eastern Lowlands===
The geology of the eastern lowlands is dominated by the ancient [[Paleozoic]] sedimentary [[Gran Chaco|Chaco]]–[[Tarija Department|Tarija]] Basin that has considerable [[Petroleum reservoir|hydrocarbon reserve]]s. During the [[Carboniferous]], the Chaco-Tarija Basin was  covered by thick [[sequence (geology)|sequence]]s that included [[sandstone]] filled channels.<ref name=B175>{{cite book|author1=A. J. Tankard|author2=Ramiro Suárez Soruco|author3=Herman J. Welsink|title=Petroleum Basins of South America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDrbYpmxZgAC&pg=PA162|year=1995|publisher=American Association of Petroleum Geologists|isbn=978-0-89181-341-5|page=175}}</ref> In the 1970s these sandstone were  interpreted as [[tillite]] from the [[Karoo Ice Age|late Paleozoic glaciations]], but new interpretations consider them to be of marine origin but still glacially influenced.<ref name=B175/> The [[Sedimentary depositional environment|depositional environment]] for these channel systems has been likened to that on the floor of the present day [[Labrador Sea]], which was influenced by repeated [[Pleistocene]] glaciations.<ref>{{cite book|author1=A. J. Tankard|author2=Ramiro Suárez Soruco|author3=Herman J. Welsink|title=Petroleum Basins of South America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDrbYpmxZgAC&pg=PA162|year=1995|publisher=American Association of Petroleum Geologists|isbn=978-0-89181-341-5|page=180}}</ref> The late [[Cenozoic]] deformation associated with the Andean orogeny forced hydrocarbons [[Source rock|sourced]] in [[Devonian]] shales to migrate to shallower [[stratigraphy|stratigraphical]] levels.<ref>{{cite book|author1=A. J. Tankard|author2=Ramiro Suárez Soruco|author3=Herman J. Welsink|title=Petroleum Basins of South America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDrbYpmxZgAC&pg=PA162|year=1995|publisher=American Association of Petroleum Geologists|isbn=978-0-89181-341-5|page=178}}</ref>

===Northern Lowlands===
{{see also|Ucayali Peneplain}}
The Northern Lowlands are and have long been a [[deposition (geology)|depositional]] milleau are mostly covered by Tertiary and Quaternary deposits. The bulk of these deposits are now [[laterite]]s. River [[erosion]] and [[sediment transport]] have created a large number of [[oxbow lake]]s and added copious [[meander]]s to the rivers.

==Guaporé Shield==

In the north and east of [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz Department]] the crystalline and [[Precambrian]] Guaporé Shield (also called Central Brazil Shield)<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0301926881900279|title=The proterozoic history of eastern Bolivia|journal=Precambrian Research|volume=15|issue=2|pages=157|doi=10.1016/0301-9268(81)90027-9|year=1981|last1=Litherland|first1=M|last2=Bloomfield|first2=K}}</ref> makes up most of the [[bedrock]] but is mostly covered by [[Tertiary]] [[laterite]]s  and [[Quaternary]] [[alluvium|alluvial]] basins.<ref>[http://www.osvaldoarce.com/summary.html METALLIFEROUS ORE DEPOSITS OF BOLIVIA]</ref> The shield expresses itself topographically as a large elevated [[hinterland]] located north of [[Serranías Chiquitanas]] towards the Brazilian border. High-grade metamorphic rocks occur in the Bolivian part of the Guaporé Shield partly due to the 2000 millions years old "Trans-Amazonian tectonothermal event" that affected parts of South America. Low-grade metamorphic rocks occur as well. The Guaporé Shield is believed to extend beneath the [[Phanerozoic]] Tarija-Chaco and [[Beni River|Beni Basin]] sediments into the Andes. It has been suggested that weaknesses in the shield were responsible for the formation of the [[Andes#Geology|Arica Elbow]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} The East-West Río Mercedes Line in the Guaporé Shield hosts several [[Proterozoic]] [[diabase]] [[intrusion]]s. As of 1985 the rocks of Guaporé Shield were considered to be poorly known.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0301926885900762|title=The southern border of the Guaporé Shield in western Brazil and Bolivia: An interpretation of its geologic evolution|journal=Precambrian Research|volume=28|issue=2|pages=111|doi=10.1016/0301-9268(85)90076-2|year=1985|last1=Jones|first1=J.P}}</ref> Near the Brazilian border the iron deposit of [[El Mutún]] stands out as the world's largest [[iron ore]] deposit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/loc-65228.html|title=Serrania Mutun, Chiquitos Province, Santa Cruz Department,  Bolivia |publisher=mindat.org |accessdate=2006-10-20}}</ref> It is located in the Serranía de El Mutún, also called Cerro Mutún or Serranía de Jacadigo in Brazil. The shield also underlies Serrania Caparuch or Huanchaca which is the inspiration for the ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|Lost World]]'' of [[Conan Doyle]].<ref>The geologic and geomorphic evolution of Serrania Huanchaca, eastern Bolivia: the legendary 'Lost World'. M Litherland and G Power: Journal of South American Earth Sciences, Vol 2, No 1, 1–17, 1989.</ref>

Proyecto Precámbrico,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.bgs.ac.uk/research/international/MathersReports/WC91-025_LatinAm.pdf |archive-url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:0HcF_RSIWugJ:https://www.bgs.ac.uk/research/international/MathersReports/WC91-025_LatinAm.pdf |archive-date=13 November 2006 |title=BGS Technical Cooperation in Latin America (1965–90) |journal=British Geological Survey Technical Report |editor-last=Mathers |editor-first=S J |number=WC191125 |date=1991 |pages=19–28 |access-date=8 April 2017 |format=PDF}}</ref> an Anglo-Bolivian technical cooperation project, explored the area between 1976 and 1986. There are a series of published 1:250,000 scale maps of the area with accompanying bilingual reports, along with more detailed 1:100,000 maps of regions of economic interest. There is a published geochemical atlas. Most of this data is summarised in an "Overseas Memoir" of the [[British Geological Survey]].<ref>''The Geology and Mineral Resources of the Bolivian Precambrian Shield''. M Litherland and others: Overseas Memoir 9, British Geological Survey, Her Majesty's Stationery Office, 1986.</ref>

