{{About|the region in Nepal|other uses|Langtang (disambiguation)}}

{{one source|date=January 2016}}
[[File:Starry night in Langtang National Park.jpg|thumb|Starry night in Langtang National Park]]
[[File:Langtang village.jpg|thumb|[[Langtang, Bagmati|Langtang village]] before it was destroyed by an avalanche caused by an earthquake in 2015]]
[[File:Gosainkunda Lake.jpg|thumb|[[Gosainkunda]] Lake]]
[[File:Kyanjin Gompa.jpg|thumb|Kyanjin Gompa]]

'''Langtang''' is a region in the [[Himalayas]] of [[Nepal]] to the north of the [[Kathmandu Valley]] and bordering [[Tibet]].

The [[Langtang National Park]] is located in the area.
About 4,500 people live inside the park, and many more depend on it for timber and firewood. The majority of the residents are [[Tamang]].

The park contains a wide variety of climatic zones, from subtropical to alpine. Approximately 25% of the park is forested. Trees include the deciduous [[oak]] and [[maple]], and evergreens like [[pine]], and various types of [[rhododendron]]. Animal life includes [[Asiatic black bear|Himalayan black bear]], the goat-like [[Himalayan tahr]], [[rhesus macaque|rhesus monkeys]] and [[red panda]]s. There are also stories of [[Yeti]] sightings.

The park contains the [[Gosainkunda]] lakes, sacred to [[Hindu]]s. Pilgrimages are made there in August. Another spiritual site is the [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] monastery [[Kyanjin Gompa]].

Popular activities for tourists in the park include trekking, [[mountain climbing|climbing]], and [[rafting|white-water rafting]].

[[Langtang, Bagmati|Langtang village]] has been completely swiped away by a massive [[avalanche]] followed by the [[May 2015 Nepal earthquake|earthquake in April 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/17/nepal-earthquake-langtang-village-everyone-was-dead|title=Nepal earthquake: the village wiped off the map in a few terrifying seconds|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=May 16, 2015|publisher=The Guardian|language=English|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> The village suffered an estimated 310 deaths, including 176 Langtang residents, 80 foreigners, and 10 army personnel. More than 100 bodies were never recovered.

