{{multiple images
| footer    = An example of the [[coastline paradox]]. If the coastline of Britain is measured using a scale interval of 200 km (left), then the length of the coastline is about 2400 km. Using a scale interval of 50 km (right), the length of the coastline is about 3400 km.
| direction = horizo
