{{About|the tool|the nuclear testing program|Operation Plumbbob}} {{Redirect|Plumbline}} [[File:Plumb bob.jpg|thumb|upright|A plumb-bob]] A '''plumb bob''', or '''plummet''', is a weight, usually with a pointed tip on the bottom, suspended from a string and used as a vertical reference line, or '''plumb-line'''. It is essentially the vertical equivalent of a "[[spirit level|water level]]".
The [[measuring instrument|instrument]] has been used since at least the time of [[ancient Egypt]]<ref name="Stocks2003">Denys A. Stocks. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=oLDuHvQODoIC&pg=PA180 Experiments in Egyptian archaeology: stoneworking technology in ancient Egypt]''. Routledge; 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-415-30664-5}}. p. 180.</ref> to ensure that constructions are "[[wikt:plumb|plumb]]", or vertical. It is also used in [[surveying]], to establish the [[nadir]] with respect to gravity of a point in space. It is used with a variety of instruments (including levels, [[theodolite]]s, and [[tape measure|steel tapes]]) to set the instrument exactly over a fixed [[survey marker]] or to transcribe positions onto the ground for placing a marker.<ref name="Brinker1995">{{cite book |title=The surveying handbook|pages=93–94|editor1-last=Brinker|editor1-first=Russell Charles|editor2-last=Minnick|editor2-first=Roy|isbn=978-0-412-98511-9|year=1995|publisher=Springer}}</ref>
== Etymology == [[File:Cc&j-fig23--plumb rule.png|upright=0.4|thumb|left|A plumb rule from the book Cassells' Carpentry and Joinery]] [[File:Cc&j-fig24--plumb square.png|thumb|A plumb square from the book Cassells' Carpentry and Joinery]] The "plumb" in "plumb-bob" comes from the fact that such tools were originally made of [[lead]] ([[Latin]]: ''[[wikt:plumbum|plumbum]]'', [[French language|French]]: ''[[wikt:plomb|plomb]]''). The adjective "[[wikt:plumb|plumb]]" developed by extension, as did the noun "[[wikt:aplomb|aplomb]]," from the notion of "standing upright."
==Use== Until the modern age, plumb-bobs were used on most tall structures to provide vertical datum lines for the building measurements. A section of the scaffolding would hold a plumb line, which was centered over a datum mark on the floor. As the building proceeded upward, the plumb line would also be taken higher, still centered on the datum. Many cathedral [[spire]]s, [[domes]] and [[tower]]s still have brass datum marks inlaid into their floors, which signify the center of the structure above.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}
[[File:Lot hg.jpg|thumb|Plumb-bob with scale as an inclinometer]] Although a plumb-bob and line alone can determine only a vertical if they are mounted on a suitable scale, the instrument may also be used as an [[inclinometer]] to measure angles to the vertical.
The early skyscrapers used heavy plumb-bobs, hung on wire in their elevator shafts.
A plumb bob may be in a container of water (when conditions are above freezing temperatures), molasses, very viscous oils or other liquids to dampen any swinging movement,<ref>Staley, W. W.. ''Introduction to mine surveying'',. 2nd ed. Stanford University, Calif.: Stanford University Press, 1964. Print. 138.</ref> functioning as a [[shock absorber]].
=== Determining center of gravity of an irregular shape === Students of [[figure drawing]] will also make use of a plumb line to find the vertical axis through the [[center of gravity]] of their subject and lay it down on paper as a [[frame of reference|point of reference]]. The device used may be purpose-made plumb lines, or simply makeshift devices made from a piece of string and a weighted object, such as a [[washer (hardware)|metal washer]]. This plumb line is important for lining up anatomical geometries and visualizing the subject's [[center of mass|center of balance]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}
== See also == *[[Bob (physics)]] *[[Centre of mass]] – used to find the centre of mass on a 2D shape (flat object) which has uniform density *[[Chalk line]] *[[Gravity direction]] *[[Vertical direction]]
